owledge, because then they could check off their quotas and move on. This w=
as bad. Wells Fargo paid a lot of fines and went through a lot of public re=
nding of garments.The problem, it seemed to me, was that Wells Fargo =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0a giant company with thousands of employees =E2=80=94=C2=A0was stu=
ck managing its employees by crude metrics (how many =E2=80=9Csolutions=E2=
=80=9D they opened) rather than with a nuanced understanding of the busines=
