I wrote yesterday about banks lending money to finance synthetic risk trans=
fer trades: A bank will have a bunch of loans, it will sell the credit risk=
 of those loans to some hedge fund, and the hedge fund will borrow money (i=
n the repo market) from another bank to finance part of its purchase. I gav=
e a schematic capital structure of the trade, suggesting that the hedge fun=
d bears the first loss on the trade and the financing bank bears the second=
 loss. (The original bank takes the third loss.) At least two people wrote =
in to complain that that is a little=C2=A0too=C2=A0schematic: The financing=
 bank only bears the second loss if (1) loan defaults eat through more than=
 all of the hedge fund=E2=80=99s equity in the trade=C2=A0and=C2=A0(2) the =
hedge fund doesn=E2=80=99t pay the bank back with its other money. That is,=
 the bank is unlikely to give the hedge fund nonrecourse financing on this =
trade. Also, as I said in a footnote, the financing bank is presumably mark=
ing the position to market and calling for margin if the underlying loans d=
eteriorate, meaning that in practice it will not bear any loss unless thing=
s go really wrong.So my schematic version overstates the risk to the bankin=
g system of this financing: Even if the SRT goes bad, the financing bank is=
 unlikely to lose much money. But it=E2=80=99s not impossible, and in parti=
cular, it=E2=80=99s a worrying sort of=C2=A0systemic=C2=A0risk. If all the =
SRTs go bad at once, hedge funds that do a lot of SRT trades really might n=
ot be able to pay back their repo lenders, and at exactly the worst time.
 =20
   =20
      Corporate chess
   =20
 =20
I have mentioned a few times the stylized fact
  [6]
=C2=A0that Susquehanna International Group employs a guy whose essential co=
ntribution to the business is that he can flip a fair coin and have it land=
 on heads 55% of the time. =E2=80=9CProp trading firms have a surprisingly =
robust demand for skilled coin flippers,=E2=80=9D I once wrote. Coin flippi=
ng, and particularly having an edge=C2=A0in coin flipping, illustrates some=
thing deep in the nature of quantitative trading, and having a guy around t=
o provide that illustration is obscurely valuable.
  [7]
=C2=A0I guess chess is a little like that too? If you are a certain sort of=
 intellectual workplace =E2=80=94=C2=A0a quant trading firm, say, or a big =
tech company =E2=80=94=C2=A0you will want to recruit the sort of people who=
 are impressed by chess skill: people who are good at chess themselves, or =
people who are good at math and logical reasoning and understand chess as a=
 sort of conventional proxy for those skills. If you have enough talented q=
uantitative employees, probably a few of them will be good at chess. But to=
 attract more, it might help to have a strong grandmaster lying around. The=
 grandmaster doesn=E2=80=99t necessarily have to do much trading or coding =
or whatever; you can just trot her out as a recruiting prop. =E2=80=9COh th=
at firm has great chess players, it must be a good place for me to work=E2=
=80=9D is a thought process that will occur in some of the employees you wa=
nt, and the cost of employing a chess grandmaster=C2=A0is probably a lot lo=
wer than the cost of employing a good quantitative trader.In somewhat relat=
ed news, here is a Wall Street Journal story about the FIDE World Corporate=
 Chess Championship:Teams from Goldman, Google, Deutsche Bank and BlackRock=
, among others, are vying not for prize money, but to be recognized by ches=
s=E2=80=99s world governing body as the =E2=80=9Csmartest company in the wo=
rld.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=A6Squads are also allowed to bring one nonemploye=
e. So just like corporate softball, where it isn=E2=80=99t unusual for team=
s to show up with someone who arouses suspicion by mashing the ball like Aa=
ron Judge, corporate chess has ringers. And the king of the ringers this ye=
ar is an American named Sam Shankland.Not only is he a grandmaster, Shankla=
nd is also a former U.S. national champion. He has published books on passe=
d pawns and training guides on the Berlin Defense. In other words, this isn=
=E2=80=99t a man who has time for a day job. Being a world-class chess play=
er is his day job. And this weekend, he just happens to be doing it for Sus=
quehanna International Group, a high-speed trading firm.=E2=80=9CChess is a=
 big part of the culture at SIG,=E2=80=9D said team captain Ella Papanek, w=
ho had previously skippered the chess team at Harvard. =E2=80=9CAt least 10=
% of the firm plays chess in some capacity.=E2=80=9DStill, when she found t=
hat a Susquehanna employee was friends with Shankland, she jumped at the ch=
ance to invite him. (Susquehanna said that Shankland isn=E2=80=99t being pa=
id.)Really they should pay him at least as much as they pay the coin flippe=
r.
 =20
   =20
      Still also golf though
   =20
 =20
I mean obviously:People who can smash 300-yard drives and sink birdie putts=
 are sought-after hires in finance, consulting, sales and other industries,=
 recruiters say. In the hybrid work era, the business golf outing is back i=
n a big way.=C2=A0Executive recruiter Shawn Cole says he gets so many reque=
sts to find ace golfers that he records candidates=E2=80=99 handicaps, an i=
ndex based on average number of strokes over par, in the information packet=
s he submits to clients. Golf alone can=E2=80=99t get you a plum job, he sa=
ys=E2=80=94but not playing could cost you one.=E2=80=9CI know a guy that li=
terally flies around the world in a private jet loaded with French wine, an=
d he golfs and lands hundred-million-dollar deals,=E2=80=9D Cole says. =E2=
=80=A6A financial adviser at a major Wall Street bank who competes on the a=
mateur circuit told me he completes 90% of his tasks by 10 a.m. because he =
manages long-term investment plans that change infrequently. The rest of hi=
s workday often involves golfing with clients and prospects. He=E2=80=99s a=
 member of a private club with a multiyear waiting list, and people jump at=
 the chance to join him on a course they normally can=E2=80=99t access.I su=
ppose in the very long run, as artificial intelligence improves,=C2=A0quant=
 investing might become a job with one hour a day of researching alpha sign=
als and seven hours a day of chess and flipping coins. But for now, private=
 wealth management is one hour a day of investing and seven hours a day of =
golf.
 =20
   =20
      Things happen
