  [1] That discrepancy is a little odd, as it seems to me that moving to Te=
xas is a much bigger deal than approving Musk=E2=80=99s pay, and I would ha=
ve expected some institutional shareholders to say =E2=80=9CI think it=E2=
=80=99s only fair to give Musk the money he earned, but I want the protecti=
ons of Delaware law.=E2=80=9D But proxy adviser Institutional Shareholder S=
ervices did recommend in favor of the move to Texas (but against the pay pa=
ckage), so it really is plausible that there=E2=80=99s more institutional s=
upport for Texas than for the pay package. Also, I am not sure what Musk=E2=
=80=99s graphs count; it=E2=80=99s conceivable that the pay graph doesn=E2=
=80=99t include Musk=E2=80=99s (and his brother=E2=80=99s) own shares, beca=
use the pay package requires the approval of a majority of the non-Musk sha=
res, and this could explain the larger number of votes for Texas (where Mus=
k=E2=80=99s own shares count). My favorite explanation, though, is: =E2=80=
=9CThese are the people who agree with Elon that the Chancery Court stole h=
is money and gave it to them, but don=E2=80=99t want to give it back.=E2=80=
=9D You could rationally conclude that moving to Texas and giving Elon Musk=
 a freer hand with Tesla would be good for the company going forward, but t=
hat you=E2=80=99d rather have the billions of dollars of options back.


  [2] =E2=80=9CThe most entertaining outcome is the most likely,=E2=80=9D i=
s Musk=E2=80=99s mantra, and my mantra when it comes to Musk. Before today,=
 I figured the most entertaining outcome would be a too-close-to-call vote,=
 demands for recounts, and a process thrown into chaos. Now the most entert=
aining outcome would be =E2=80=9Che tweets Tesla is winning by wide margins=
, and then it loses by wide margins, and then he gets sued.=E2=80=9D Also I=
 wonder if Musk=E2=80=99s Twitter sitter reviewed this tweet.


  [3] See section 266 of the Delaware General Corporation Law.


  [4] From the proxy: =E2=80=9CDelaware common law ratification permits a D=
elaware corporation to validate a corporate act where the actors that purpo=
rted to effect it lacked requisite corporate authority to do so. Common law=
 ratification can also extinguish claims for breach of fiduciary duty by au=
thorizing an act that otherwise would constitute a breach. When properly im=
plemented, common law ratification =E2=80=98reaches back=E2=80=99 to valida=
te the challenged act as of its initial enactment. The Company believes tha=
t, under the Tornetta Opinion, the 2018 CEO Performance Award is such an ac=
t that may be ratified under Delaware common law.=E2=80=9D


  [5] There=E2=80=99s also the fake dinner receipt scandal of 2018.


  [6] Here =E2=80=9Cstylized fact=E2=80=9D means =E2=80=9Cjoke.=E2=80=9D


  [7] Once when I wrote about this, a reader pointed out that some people c=
an, in certain tightly controlled circumstances, achieve 100% predictabilit=
y in flipping coins, using post-flip sleight of hand. (Here=E2=80=99s a mag=
ician doing it on television.) But that is of course not what prop trading =
firms want. They want pre-flip sleight of hand, for one thing, but also the=
y want probabilistic edge, not certainty.


