 =E2=80=9Cconstantly hound, berate, demean and threaten employees to meet t=
hese unreachable quotas.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so th=
e employees, rather than working with each customer to build a suite of pro=
ducts that met the customer=E2=80=99s needs and deepened her relationship w=
ith the bank, would just go and open a bunch of fake accounts. They=E2=80=
=99d sign the customer up for online banking and a credit card and a saving=
s account=C2=A0<em>without her knowledge</em>, because then they could chec=
k off their quotas and move on. This was bad. Wells Fargo paid a lot of fin=
es and went through a lot of public rending of garments.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">The problem, it seemed to me, was that Wells Fargo =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0a giant company with thousands of employees =E2=80=94=C2=A0was stuck =
managing its employees by crude metrics (how many =E2=80=9Csolutions=E2=80=
=9D they opened) rather than with a nuanced understanding of the business a=
