</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have occasionally, as a writer about=
 finance and a former equity derivatives banker, made fun of structured not=
es. A structured note is essentially a package sold by a bank to private we=
alth customers consisting of:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; pad=
ding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Some=
 option or set of options on one or more stocks, indexes, commodities or wh=
at have you;</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">An unsecured bond of =
the bank; and</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A big fee for the ba=
nk.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIf you want those option=
s,=E2=80=9D I used to think, =E2=80=9Cyou should just buy the options direc=
tly; you don=E2=80=99t want the bank=E2=80=99s unsecured credit risk and yo=
u certainly don=E2=80=99t want to pay the fee.=E2=80=9D But over time I hav=
e been talked out of that purist position. In fact, it is not always easy t=
o buy the particular options in the quantity that you want, and your tradin=
g costs might be higher than the bank=E2=80=99s. But also, what the bank is=
 doing in building the structured note is finding an <em>appealing=C2=A0</e=
m>collection=C2=A0of options, one with a good clear story, so that instead =
of going out and piecing together a complicated portfolio of options you ju=
st get a thing that is like =E2=80=9Cthe return on the S&amp;P 500 Index ov=
er the next year, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
35707099.259299/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzI=
