=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">the FIDE World Corporate Chess Championship</a>:</p><blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Teams from Goldman, Google, Deutsche Bank an=
d BlackRock, among others, are vying not for prize money, but to be recogni=
zed by chess=E2=80=99s world governing body as the =E2=80=9Csmartest compan=
y in the world.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Squ=
ads are also allowed to bring one nonemployee. So just like corporate softb=
all, where it isn=E2=80=99t unusual for teams to show up with someone who a=
rouses suspicion by mashing the ball like Aaron Judge, corporate chess has =
ringers. And the king of the ringers this year is an American named Sam Sha=
nkland.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Not only is he a grandmaster, Shank=
land is also a former U.S. national champion. He has published books on pas=
sed pawns and training guides on the Berlin Defense. In other words, this i=
sn=E2=80=99t a man who has time for a day job. Being a world-class chess pl=
ayer is his day job. And this weekend, he just happens to be doing it for S=
usquehanna International Group, a high-speed trading firm.</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CChess is a big part of the culture at SIG,=E2=80=
=9D said team captain Ella Papanek, who had previously skippered the chess =
team at Harvard. =E2=80=9CAt least 10% of the firm plays chess in some capa=
city.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, when she found that a=
 Susquehanna employee was friends with Shankland, she jumped at the chance =
to invite him. (Susquehanna said that Shankland isn=E2=80=99t being paid.)<=
/p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Really they should pay him at =
least as much as they pay the coin flipper.</p><table class=3D"header" widt=
